descript.abstract: This is a generalized Triangulated Irregular Network terrain model for a portion of Death Valley, California. It was created for use in the 3D Analyst tutorial. The source data was downloaded in SDTS format from the USGS. Several 7.5 minute DEMs were converted to GRID format, tiled, and used to georeference an SIR-C band image downloaded from the JPL website. The GRID terrain model was clipped to its curent extent, resampled to 90 meter resolution to reduce the storage volume of the data, and converted to a TIN. The TIN conversion was done with loose vertical control in order to create a simplified, lightweight TIN.
descript.purpose: This data is intended to demonstrate the use of a TIN terrain model for draping remotely-sensed imagery. The resolution and vertical accuracy of the source data has been reduced in order to keep this TIN small.

procstep.procdesc: Several 7.5 minute DEMs were downloaded in SDTS format from the USGS website. They were converted in ArcInfo 8.02 to grid format and tiled in ArcInfo 8.02 into a single grid. The grid was used to georeference a remotely sensed image, then downsampled to 90 meter resolution in ArcInfo 8.02. The grid was clipped to its current extent in ArcInfo 8.02. The clipped grid was further generalized when it was converted to a TIN in ArcGIS 3D Analyst.
